Predicting Bostonâ€™s Bikeshare Ridership

Ben Dodson

November 15, 2019

Executive Summary

Using a predictive model, Boston can understand when bikeshare trip generations will be highest, and how they fluctuate overtime. Understanding which areas of Boston have the characteristics in place to support bikeshare stations has the potential to result in a more efficient and effective operation of the service. The model can predict the number of trips generated at each bikeshare station, within about 1.25 trips. The model has possible applicationâ€™s in Bostonâ€™s transportation planning process. In areas where congestion is high and transit options are limited, this tool can quickly evaluate the success of a proposed station location. Additionally, in places where the model predicts usage should be high, but the observations show that usage is low, it would be worth investigating which factors are contributing to this. Possible factors could be station access, bike infrastructure in the vicinity, or a high population of bike owners. The model should be used as a tool to guide expansion and analysis of the system but not be used to replace these processes. The model works best when it is used as evidence to support intelligent and informed plans.

weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "BOS", date_start = "2015-06-01", date_end = "2015-08-31") %>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
  mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(interval60) %>%
  summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
            Precipitation = sum(p01i),
            Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
  mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

Bostonâ€™s bikeshare program, Bluebikes, publishes usage data on a monthly basis. The most recent data availibile is from 2015. This analysis uses June-August data from 2015 to understand bikeshare usage throughout the summer. This data has been combined with Census data from the 3 Massachusetts counties (Suffolk, Norfolk, and Middlesex). The census data includes information about total population, median income, population that self-identifies as white, average time spent traveling, means of transport to work, population that took public transport to work, and median age. The model also uses historical weather data collected at Bostonâ€™s Logan Airport.

Modeling

study.panel <- 
  expand.grid(interval60=unique(dat_census$interval60), 
              start.station.id = unique(dat_census$start.station.id)) %>%
  left_join(., dat_census %>%
              select(start.station.id, start.station.name, Origin.Tract, start.station.longitude, start.station.latitude )%>%
              distinct() %>%
              group_by(start.station.id) %>%
              slice(1))
## Joining, by = "start.station.id"
ride.panel <- 
  dat_census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
  right_join(study.panel) %>% 
  group_by(interval60, start.station.id, start.station.name, Origin.Tract, start.station.longitude, start.station.latitude) %>%
  summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>%
  left_join(weather.Panel) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is.na(start.station.id) == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(Origin.Tract) == FALSE)
## Joining, by = c("start.station.id", "start.station.name", "interval60", "Origin.Tract", "start.station.longitude", "start.station.latitude")
## Joining, by = "interval60"
ride.panel <- 
  left_join(ride.panel, bostonCensus %>%
              as.data.frame() %>%
              select(-geometry), by = c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID"))

ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start.station.id, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24)) %>%
  mutate(day = yday(interval60)) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE))

as.data.frame(ride.panel) %>%
  group_by(interval60) %>% 
  summarise_at(c(vars(starts_with("lag"), "Trip_Count")), mean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -interval60, -Trip_Count) %>%
  mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels=c("lagHour","lag2Hours","lag3Hours","lag4Hours",
                                              "lag12Hours","lag1day")))%>%
  group_by(Variable) %>%  
  summarize(correlation = round(cor(Value, Trip_Count),2))
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   Variable   correlation
##   <fct>            <dbl>
## 1 lagHour           0.8 
## 2 lag2Hours         0.5 
## 3 lag3Hours         0.27
## 4 lag4Hours         0.12
## 5 lag12Hours       -0.35
## 6 lag1day           0.8
ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week >= 29)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week < 29)
reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start.station.name +  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
       lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day, 
     data=ride.Train)

Model A (Space_FE): Starting Station, Day of the Week, Temperature

Model B (Time_Space_FE): Starting Station, Day of the Week, Temperature, Hour of the Day, Precipitation

Model C (Time_Space_FE_timeLags): Starting Station, Day of the Week, Temperature, Hour of the Day, Precipitation, Hour Time Lags

ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(-week) 

model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
  pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}

week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
  mutate(ASpace_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
         BTime_Space_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
         CTime_Space_FE_timeLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
  gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
  mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
         Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
         MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
         sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))
week_predictions %>%
  dplyr::select(week, Regression, MAE) %>%
  gather(Variable, MAE, -Regression, -week) %>%
  ggplot(aes(week, MAE)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Regression), position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette5) +
  labs(title = "Mean Absolute Errors by model specification and week") +
  plotTheme

week_predictions %>% 
  mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
         start.station.id = map(data, pull, start.station.id)) %>%
  dplyr::select(interval60, start.station.id, Observed, Prediction, Regression) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -Regression, -interval60, -start.station.id) %>%
  group_by(Regression, Variable, interval60) %>%
  summarize(Value = sum(Value)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(interval60, Value, colour=Variable)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1.1) + 
  facet_wrap(~Regression, ncol=1) +
  labs(title = "Predicted/Observed bike share time series", subtitle = "Boston; A test set of 2 weeks",  x = "Hour", y= "Station Trips") +
  plotTheme

Model C best predicts ridership with the least errors. This is the model that will be used going forward.

Discussion

Including a spatial lag in the model greatly improves the predictions but errors will still be present. For instance, there are more errors at stations where trip generation is signifigantly higher than elsewhere in the system. The model struggles most in Bostonâ€™s central business district.

week_predictions %>% 
  mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
         start.station.id = map(data, pull, start.station.id), 
         start.station.latitude = map(data, pull, start.station.latitude), 
         start.station.longitude = map(data, pull, start.station.longitude)) %>%
  select(interval60, start.station.id, start.station.longitude, start.station.latitude, Observed, Prediction, Regression) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  filter(Regression == "CTime_Space_FE_timeLags") %>%
  group_by(start.station.id, start.station.longitude, start.station.latitude) %>%
  summarize(MAE = mean(abs(Observed-Prediction), na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  ggplot(.)+
  geom_sf(data = bostonCensus, color = "grey", fill = "transparent")+
  geom_point(aes(x = start.station.longitude, y = start.station.latitude, color = MAE), 
             fill = "transparent", alpha = 1)+
  scale_colour_viridis(direction = -1,
                       discrete = FALSE, option = "D")+
  ylim(min(dat_census$start.station.latitude), max(dat_census$start.station.latitude))+
  xlim(min(dat_census$start.station.longitude), max(dat_census$start.station.longitude))+
  labs(title="Mean Abs Error, Test Set, Model 3")+
  mapTheme

The model works better on the weekends and during days when ridership is more standardized (mid-day and overnight). It struggles specifically in the PM rush because the relatively higher ridership.

Across some socioeconomic variables, the models errors are distributed. One area where the model struggles is in census tracts where the share of the population that identifies as white is a super majority or greater. This may be because census data pertaining to race deals with those that live in the census tract, however there are plenty of trips that are generated by people who do not live in the tract (ex: commute home from work).

week_predictions %>% 
  mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
         start.station.id = map(data, pull, start.station.id), 
         start.station.latitude = map(data, pull, start.station.latitude), 
         start.station.longitude = map(data, pull, start.station.longitude),
         dotw = map(data, pull, dotw),
         Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = map(data, pull, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans),
         Med_Inc = map(data, pull, Med_Inc),
         Percent_White = map(data, pull, Percent_White)) %>%
  select(interval60, start.station.id, start.station.longitude, 
         start.station.latitude, Observed, Prediction, Regression,
         dotw, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans, Med_Inc, Percent_White) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  filter(Regression == "CTime_Space_FE_timeLags")%>%
  mutate(weekend = ifelse(dotw %in% c("Sun", "Sat"), "Weekend", "Weekday"),
         time_of_day = case_when(hour(interval60) < 7 | hour(interval60) > 18 ~ "Overnight",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 10 & hour(interval60) < 15 ~ "Mid-Day",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 15 & hour(interval60) <= 18 ~ "PM Rush")) %>%
  filter(time_of_day == "AM Rush") %>%
  group_by(start.station.id, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans, Med_Inc, Percent_White) %>%
  summarize(MAE = mean(abs(Observed-Prediction), na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  gather(-start.station.id, -MAE, key = "variable", value = "value")%>%
  ggplot(.)+
  #geom_sf(data = bostonCensus, color = "grey", fill = "transparent")+
  geom_point(aes(x = value, y = MAE), alpha = 0.4)+
  geom_smooth(aes(x = value, y = MAE), method = "lm", se= FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales = "free")+
  labs(title="Errors as a function of socio-economic variables",
       y="Mean Absolute Error (Trips)")+
  plotTheme

The model has several errors but does leverage the data well. Some solutions to alleviate this would be adding more stations in the Central Business District to distribute the number of trip generations. As with any model, it struggles to predict at the extremes, in this case, during the PM peak. Another way to improve the model could be to include more data but some thought should be put in how to do this. For example, simply using an entire calendar year of data may contain many more nuances that the model could struggle with, but rather, by doing it seasonally and including several years of seasons (ex: Summer 2015, Summer 2014, etc.) could provide more insight but would struggle with year-to-year changes in trends. Understanding errors is essential to responsible model usage. Being upfront about any socioeconomic disparities in the model is also essential to unbiased model usage. However, it is important to understand the placement of bikeshare stations may be inherently biased for which the model cannot be feature engineered to fix.
